ns MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">1.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Understanding Walking and C</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ycling (UWAC) project examined the factors influencing everyday transport decisions in four English towns/cities (Leeds, Leicest</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">er, Worcester, Lancaster) and investigated why people do not choose to walk and cycle. While some of the conclusions drawn are purely sociological. i.e. it is not ‘normal’ there is a clear perception that cycling is dangerous and that only the most committ</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ed cyclists are happy to mix with other traffic.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">2.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Therefore, the question of whether cycling is safe is largely irrelevant as it is currently not perceived to be safe. It is only when these safety perceptions are changed that mass cycling in the UK will</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> be the norm.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">3.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Rather than relist the evidence presented in many other submissions, it is more succinct to say we second the recommendations made by the CTC in their written evidence (CYS 053).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">4.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Finally, it is clear that we know how to solve the safe</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ty issues, what is required is political will and sustained high investment.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">References</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Understanding walking and cycling : summary of key findings and recommendations. / Pooley, Colin; Tight, Miles; Jones, Tim; Horton, David; Scheldeman, Griet; Jopson, A</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">nn; Mullen, Caroline; Chisholm, Alison; Strano, Emanuele; Constantine, Sheila. Lancaster : Lancaster University, 2011. 21 p.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_GoBack"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">